<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1441,565,648]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis box="[826,952,565,586]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is based on the prefix 
<emphasis box="[826,879,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">para</emphasis>
(somewhat resembling, related to) and the specific epithet of the species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1138,1252,627,648]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[1138,1252,627,648]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1441,687,801]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis box="[826,945,688,709]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The species differs morphologically from its closest relative, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1062,1179,719,740]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[1062,1179,719,740]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the presence of a very large dorsal penial fold, very small ventral fold and a ventrally displaced ejaculatory duct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1441,840,954]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis box="[826,1120,840,861]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Ecology and distribution:</emphasis>
The species is known only from two sites in the same river. One site is close to the opening of this river into the sea, while the 
<typeStatus box="[1392,1441,902,923]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">type</typeStatus>
locality is located slightly farther upstream.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis box="[826,1107,993,1015]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Comparative discussion:</emphasis>
The taxonomic status of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Schmidt, 1861)" baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schmidt O" box="[925,1096,1024,1046]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref17822" refString="Schmidt O. 1861. Untersuchungen uber Turbellarien von Corfu und Cephalonia, nebst Nachtragen zu fruheren Arbeiten. Zeitschrift fur wissenschaftliche Zoologie 11: 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1861">Schmidt, 1861</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Corfu as a valid and separate species was clarified by 
<bibRefCitation author="De Vries EJ" box="[1243,1437,1054,1077]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
. Prior to her study, the 
<taxonomicName box="[1130,1222,1086,1107]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1130,1222,1086,1107]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Dugesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations from Corfu were usually considered to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[826,999,1146,1168]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis box="[826,999,1146,1168]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, following a conclusion reached by 
<bibRefCitation author="Komarek J" box="[826,1012,1177,1199]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="322 - 328" refId="ref17045" refString="Komarek J. 1925. Die O. Schmidt'schen Susswassertricladen von Corfu und Cephalonia, gesammelt von Prof. Wilhelmi. Zoologischer Anzeiger 63: 322 - 328." type="journal article" year="1925">Komárek (1925)</bibRefCitation>
. To avoid future taxonomic confusion, 
<bibRefCitation author="De Vries EJ" box="[826,1017,1207,1230]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
fortunately designated a series of 
<typeStatus box="[826,926,1239,1260]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotypes</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[986,1097,1239,1260]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[986,1097,1239,1260]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (ITZN, 1985; 
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN &amp; International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" refId="ref16928" refString="ICZN, International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature. 1999. International code of zoological nomenclature, 4 th edn. London: The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature." type="book" year="1999">ICZN, 1999</bibRefCitation>
) restricts designation of a 
<typeStatus box="[1208,1297,1300,1321]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
to only 
<specimenCount pageId="15" pageNumber="538" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
that forms the new name-bearing type of a nominal species and thus does not allow it to be a 
<emphasis box="[826,889,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">series</emphasis>
of animals, the 
<typeStatus box="[1082,1171,1391,1412]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
specimens specified by 
<bibRefCitation author="De Vries EJ" box="[826,1086,1422,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984: 104)</bibRefCitation>
represent a morphologically homogeneous set of animals. As 
<typeStatus box="[1206,1295,1453,1474]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
locality was chosen Messonghi River, just west of Messonghi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
The Ermones population was first mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ball IR" box="[826,965,1544,1566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="187 - 190" refId="ref15818" refString="Ball IR. 1979. The karyotypes of two Dugesia species from Corfu, Greece (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria). Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 48: 187 - 190." type="journal article" year="1979">Ball (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, who attributed it to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[1261,1434,1544,1566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis box="[1261,1434,1544,1566]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the same paper the karyotype of presumed 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Duges" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[826,999,1605,1627]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gonocephala">
<emphasis box="[826,999,1605,1627]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. gonocephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Corfu was analysed but it is not clear which population was studied, either the one from Ermones or the animals from Messonghi River. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="De Vries EJ" box="[944,1129,1697,1719]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" pagination="101 - 126" refId="ref16283" refString="De Vries EJ. 1984. On the species of the Dugesia gonocephala group (Platyhelminthes, Turbellaria, Tricladida) from Greece. Bijdragen tot de Dierkunde 54: 101 - 126." type="journal article" year="1984">De Vries (1984)</bibRefCitation>
writes that animals from the 
<typeStatus box="[882,971,1728,1749]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">neotype</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[1130,1241,1728,1749]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[1130,1241,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, i.e. Messonghi River, were analysed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[826,1442,993,1902]" lastBlockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="539" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
Our integrative analysis of the populations that we sampled from Corfu revealed an unexpected and interesting situation. Molecular analysis of both COI and ITS-1 grouped the various populations sampled into three clades (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sola E &amp; Sluys R &amp; Gritzalis K &amp; Riutort M" box="[401,596,198,220]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" pagination="877 - 888" refId="ref18036" refString="Sola E, Sluys R, Gritzalis K, Riutort M. 2013. Fluvial basin history in the northeastern Mediterranean Region underlies dispersal and speciation patterns in the genus Dugesia (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Dugesiidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 66: 877 - 888." type="journal article" year="2013">
Solà 
<emphasis box="[462,511,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">et al</emphasis>
., 2013
</bibRefCitation>
). These three clades are also identified as separate entities in the GMYC analysis (
<figureCitation box="[338,405,259,281]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
, entities 1, 2 and 3). One clade was formed by populations 27, 28, 29 and 30 (i.e. north of the San Salvador mountain range). The second clade consisted of populations 33 and 34. The third clade consisted of two samples from basically the same locality, namely Ermones (localities 31 and 32) (
<figureCitation box="[197,283,443,465]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. S2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5297137" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5297137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5297137/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" startId="15.[164,243,1824,1843]" targetBox="[166,775,1338,1794]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[164,779,1824,1902]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[164,281,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Figure 13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" box="[292,681,1824,1843]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[292,533,1824,1843]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">Dugesia parasagitta</emphasis>
Sluys &amp; Solà
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[690,779,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[690,779,1824,1843]" pageId="15" pageNumber="538" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Photomicrograph of large dorsal penial fold in specimen ZMA V.Pl. 7118.1.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
On the basis of morphological analysis of the populations from Corfu we were able to differentiate between only 
<specimenCount box="[306,422,535,556]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
. The majority of the populations sampled conformed to the classical diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[144,254,596,617]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[144,254,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, notably in the presence of a well-developed dorsal fold and a very small or absent ventral fold, and with a central ejaculatory duct. This also holds true for populations that we have not re-collected, but of which material is present in the collections of the NBC: Messonghi River, Marbella beach (now called Par. Ag. Ioannis Peristeron) and Mesaria. However, the population from Ermones (ZMA V.Pl. 7118 + V.Pl. 7119) is characterized by a very large dorsal penial fold, very small ventral fold and a ventrally displaced ejaculatory duct (
<figureCitation box="[348,428,901,924]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="15.[164,243,1824,1843]" captionTargetBox="[166,775,1338,1794]" captionTargetId="figure-688@15.[166,776,1338,1794]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 13. Dugesia parasagitta Sluys &amp; Solà sp. nov. Photomicrograph of large dorsal penial fold in specimen ZMA V.Pl. 7118.1." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5297137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5297137/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Thus, coincidence of molecular and morphological results suggests that at least the population from Ermones is well differentiated from other populations on Corfu. Therefore, we do here describe this population as the new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" box="[144,310,1055,1076]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta">
<emphasis box="[144,310,1055,1076]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. parasagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
It remains remarkable that the populations that are geographically closest to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[522,632,1116,1137]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[522,632,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type locality, namely ZMA V.Pl. 7120 from near Vouniatades (locality 33) and ZMA V.Pl. 7121 from near Benitses (34) (entity 2, 
<figureCitation box="[306,373,1207,1230]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), differ molecularly so much from the populations in the northern part of the island (entity 1, 
<figureCitation box="[285,351,1269,1291]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), whereas morphologically they cannot be distinguished from each other, nor from the 
<typeStatus box="[144,233,1330,1351]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">neotype</typeStatus>
population.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[144,759,198,1903]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">
After the separation and description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sluys &amp; Sola" authorityYear="2013" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parasagitta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. parasagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the nominal species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[474,585,1392,1413]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[474,585,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
actually forms a paraphyletic taxon, according to all molecular analyses done so far (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sola E &amp; Sluys R &amp; Gritzalis K &amp; Riutort M" box="[441,632,1452,1474]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" pagination="877 - 888" refId="ref18036" refString="Sola E, Sluys R, Gritzalis K, Riutort M. 2013. Fluvial basin history in the northeastern Mediterranean Region underlies dispersal and speciation patterns in the genus Dugesia (Platyhelminthes, Tricladida, Dugesiidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 66: 877 - 888." type="journal article" year="2013">
Solà 
<emphasis box="[502,550,1452,1474]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">et al</emphasis>
., 2013
</bibRefCitation>
; COI gene tree, 
<figureCitation box="[205,272,1483,1505]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, the geographical distribution of the various populations (
<figureCitation box="[509,589,1513,1535]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. S2</figureCitation>
) suggests that these two units form two independent lineages. In view of the definition of a species as an independently evolving lineage, this suggests that these lineages are actually two different species. We do take a conservative approach to taxonomy and do not assign formal species status to these taxa, pending the availability of further data. However, we do suggest that entity 2 (from localities 33 and 34, i.e. in the proximity of the 
<typeStatus box="[192,281,1789,1810]" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">neotype</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[418,529,1789,1810]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[418,529,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is assigned to the nominal species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schmidt" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[343,454,1820,1841]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Dugesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="16" pageNumber="539" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagitta">
<emphasis box="[343,454,1820,1841]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">D. sagitta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and that entity 1 (from localities 27 and 29) represents a UCS (
<figureCitation box="[661,754,1850,1872]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[164,243,967,986]" captionTargetBox="[322,1282,196,938]" captionTargetId="graphics-198@7.[322,1068,196,937]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 2. Result of the GMYC analysis. Threshold-delimiting speciation and coalescent processes plotted as a broken line. Numbers indicate molecular-based entities; labels correspond to species names. Entities in green show correspondence between the molecular species delimitation method and the morphologically identified species. In orange are shown groupings where there is conflict between morphological and molecular methods. In blue are shown the groupings for which only molecular data are available." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5290985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5290985/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Fig. S2</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[144,226,1880,1903]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="5.[164,228,198,217]" captionText="Table 1. Clusters obtained in the GMYC analysis" pageId="16" pageNumber="539">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
